NumSpaceHeroBadges indicates a strong positive effect, keeping all other variables in the model constant. The likelihood of a gamer investing in the Salon campaign appears to rise with each badge earned. This trend may reflect the gamer’s proficiency and active participation in the game.

Conversely, NumFriendRequestIgnored and TimesLostSpaceShip suggest negative effects, keeping all other variables in the model constant. As the frequency of ignored friend requests and instances of losing a spaceship go up, there’s an implied decrease in the possibility of a gamer purchasing the Salon campaign. These patterns could be indicative of lesser skill and a potentially reduced level of engagement within the game.

We see positive effects for GameLevel and NumAdsClicked, keeping all other variables in the model constant. With the increase in GameLevel and the number of ads clicked, there seems to be an uptick in the gamer’s chances of engaging with the Salon campaign. Advancement in game levels may signify a player’s skill and commitment, whereas interacting with advertisements may indicate an openness to new promotions.

Part III: The Ad-Experiment (12 points)

You have finished building a logistic regression model to predict what kind of Space Pirates gamers were more or less likely to purchase the Zalon campaign. After debriefing Mi Haruki on the performance of the predictive model, she lays out the next steps:

“We will test the effectiveness of the in-app ad and the predictive model by exposing a random 150,000 customers to a 2-week ad campaign and measuring their conversion to Zalon over the next 2 months. At the same time, we will randomly pick another 30,000 customers and observe their organic upgrade behavior over the same period. This set of customers will not be served any in-app ads.

I want you to compare three groups based on this data.

Group 1: The randomly picked 30,000 Space Pirates gamers who did not receive in-app ads during the experimental period.

Group 2: A randomly picked 30,000 Space Pirates gamers among the 150,000 who were served in-app ads for Zalon.

Group 3: A model-selected 30,000 Space Pirates gamers among the 120,000 (after taking out Group 2) who were served in-app ads for Zalon.

Please report back to me how well the ads are working in terms of conversion rates and profits and by how much the model improves these metrics, all based on targeting 30,000 customers. To calculate profits, please use revenues of $14.99 from selling Zalon. The cost of serving ads to a consumer for 2 weeks is $1.50 in lost coin purchases.”

In the context of the ad experiment conducted, the impact on conversion rates and profitability across the three distinct groups showed varied outcomes.

Group 1, which comprised 30,000 Space Pirates gamers who were not exposed to any in-app advertisements, exhibited a conversion rate of 5.69%. The revenue generated by this group, absent any advertising cost, culminated in a profit of $25,573.

When examining Group 2, which also consisted of 30,000 Space Pirates gamers but from the subset that did receive in-app advertisements for Zalon, there was an elevation in the conversion rate to 13.04%. However, when considering the associated costs of running the ads, the profit for this group experienced a downturn, settling at $13,656.

Group 3, the cohort selected by the predictive model from the remaining 120,000 gamers who were served ads, demonstrated the potency of targeted advertising. The conversion rate soared to 21.51% for these gamers. More importantly, the profit escalated dramatically to $51,715, even after factoring in the costs of advertising.

Analyzing the financial benefit of the ad campaign, particularly when leveraging the predictive model for customer selection, reveals a substantial gain. Specifically, the profit for Group 3 exceeds that of Group 1 by $26,143, illustrating the added value of data-driven targeting in advertising strategies. This result underscores the efficacy of the predictive model in not only enhancing conversion rates but also in substantially improving profit margins.

The outcomes from the gains curve and Area Under the Curve (AUC) metric for the customer set excluding Group 2 (those indicated by rnd_30k == 0) are observed to be diminished when compared to the results obtained in Part II. This discrepancy can be attributed to the differing contexts in which the model was applied.

During Part II, the model was both trained and evaluated on data reflecting organic conversion behaviors. In Part III, although we used the same model, we predictive the model by exposing to a 2-week ad campaign. This shift in the prediction environment could be the primary cause for the reduced performance metrics seen in Part III.

The concept of “situational invariance” is crucial here — it refers to the assumption that the conditions under which a model is trained should ideally be consistent with the conditions under which it is tested. Since the model was originally calibrated to predict organic adoption without the presence of ad, its application to a situation where ad influence is present does not align with the original training context. Consequently, the model’s predictive accuracy is naturally expected to be lower in scenarios where the influencing factors differ from those in the training data.

  1. What could be the value of collecting data for group 1 (cg_organic_control) given that we already had data on organic conversions from the cg_organic data? (2 points)

Probability of organically converting to Zalon (cg_organic) - 5.75%

Response rate of group 1 (cg_organic_control) - 5.68%

The collection of Group 1 data, termed “cg_organic_control,” serves as a vital contemporary benchmark, even with prior information on organic conversion trends from “cg_organic.” This data acts as a fresh control group, crucial for assessing the current market conditions and user responses which may have evolved from the period when the previous organic data was collected. The consistency in conversion rates — 5.75% previously observed in “cg_organic” and 5.68% found during the experiment in “cg_organic_control” — suggests stability in the market dynamics during the two data collection intervals. This stability allows for a reliable comparison of the effects of recent marketing interventions, such as in-app advertising, against a current and relevant baseline.

Part IV: Better Data, Better Predictions (8 points)

Mi Hiruki called for a meeting to discuss next steps. She explained: “Before we roll out the campaign globally, we want to see whether we can use the experimental data to retrain the model. The idea is to model trial in response to the in-app ad—not just organic conversion as we did initially. We know that the in-app ad, on average, increases Zalon conversions. However, if the in-app ad works for people who would not have purchased the Zalon campaign organically, updating the model based on the in-app ad data should improve predictive performance.

Let’s retrain the model based on the randomly chosen Space Pirates gamers we messaged in the experiment and see how well the updated model compares to the original model in a test sample.”

AUC for “organic” model on test set - 0.644

AUC for new “ad” model on test set - 0.703

The comparison between the “organic” and “ad” models in terms of AUC values - 0.644 for the organic and 0.703 for the ad model - highlights the concept of situational invariance. This concept refers to the idea that a model’s effectiveness can vary depending on the context or environment in which it is applied.

In this case, the “organic” model, developed under normal conditions without advertising influence, performs less effectively in an environment where ad campaigns are active. The “ad” model, on the other hand, is specifically tailored for the scenario where customers are exposed to ads, hence its higher AUC value.

Examining the gains curves, where the “ad” model’s curve ascends more steeply than the “organic” model’s. This indicates that the “ad” model is more proficient at identifying and engaging with potential customers who are more responsive to the advertising, thus leading to a higher concentration of conversions earlier in the targeting process.

This difference underscores the importance of adapting predictive models to the specific circumstances in which they will be used, as a model that works well in one situation might not perform as effectively in another.
